<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900619-0138</DOCNO><DOCID>900619-0138.</DOCID><HL>   South Africa's Trade Surplus</HL><DATE>06/19/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AFRIC</CO><IN>MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><LP>   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- South Africa's trade surpluswidened to 1.08 billion rand ($404.9 million) in May from 333million rand a year earlier and from 969 million rand inApril, the government's Customs and Excise Office said.   The figures aren't seasonally adjusted, but export andimport data are adjusted to bring them in line with therequirements for compiling the nation's balance of payments.</LP><TEXT>   May exports totaled 4.69 billion rand, compared with 4.46billion rand a year earlier, and imports amounted to 3.6billion rand, compared with 4.13 billion rand.   In the first five months of this year, exports amounted to23.71 billion rand, compared with 21.93 billion rand a yearearlier, and imports totaled 17.62 billion rand, comparedwith 17.8 billion rand.   The trade figures include South Africa's exports of goldbullion, the country's principal source of foreign exchangeearnings. Imports include the country's purchases of oil andother petroleum products, despite the longstanding embargo ofthe Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.</TEXT></DOC>